<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-06-14T19:13:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-06-14T19:13:00-05:00" n="636" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d636">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861a.01/10: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vladivostok</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vladivostok</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-15T09:00:00+08:47"><hi rend="italic">June 15, 1920—9
                                    a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 11:15 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>199. Copies Tokyo, Peking. Department’s telegram June 11, 1 p.m.<note n="79" xml:id="d636fn79">Not printed.</note> Vladivostok
                                provisional government recognizes Far Eastern Republic at
                                Verkhneudinsk and their relations are good. Both announce desire for
                                union as soon as Semenoff barrier removed but no mention so far of
                                terms on which this could be effected.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>